SIMPLE: resuscitate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Resuscitate
<hw>Re*sus"ci*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>resuscitatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>resuscitare</ets>; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>suscitare</ets> to raise, rouse. See
<er>Suscitate</er>.]</ety> <def>Restored to life.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Gardiner.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resuscitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Resuscitate
<hw>Re*sus"ci*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Resuscitated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Resuscitating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To revivify; to revive;
especially, to recover or restore from apparent death; <as>as, to
<ex>resuscitate</ex> a drowned person; to <ex>resuscitate</ex> withered
plants.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resuscitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Resuscitate
<hw>Re*sus"ci*tate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To come to life again; to
revive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These projects, however often slain, always
<qex>resuscitate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. S. Mill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resuscitation</ent>⟦br⟧
